ics as the rules of conduct for Ottoman Jewish sea traders, the trials of an ex-husband accused of a robbery, and the rights of a sexually abused wife. Goldish provides a sizeable introduction to the history of the Sephardic diaspora and the nature of responsa literature, as well as a bibliography, historical background for each question, and short biographies of the rabbis involved. Including cases from well-known communities such as Venice, Istanbul, and Saloniki, and lesser-known Jewish enclaves such as Kastoria, Ragusa, and Nablus, Jewish Questions provides a sense of how Sephardic communities were organized, how Jews related to their neighbors, what problems threatened them and their families, and how they understood their relationship to God and the Jewish people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJewszTurkeyxHistoryvSources. 0aSephardimzTurkeyxHistoryvSources. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAdmonition.  aAdultery.  aAge of majority.  aAgunah.  aAlgiers.  aAnnulment.  aApostasy.  aAristotelianism.  aBathing.  aBenveniste.  aBibliography.  aBigamy.  aBlood libel.  aBook of Leviticus.  aChristendom.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aConcubinage.  aConversion to Judaism.  aConverso.  aCrucifixion of Jesus.  aCrypto-Judaism.  aDebasement.  aDebtor.  aDecree.  aDefamation.  aDisease.  aDomestic violence.  aDowry.  aEarly modern period.  aEmbarrassment.  aEngagement.  aExcommunication.  aExpatriate.  aFeudalism.  aGentile.  aHakham.  aHeresy.  aHouse of Habsburg.  aIdolatry.  aInjunction.  aJewish history.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aKabbalah.  aKaraite Judaism.  aKastoria (regional unit).  aKaunos.  aKetubah.  aKetubot (tractate).  aKohen.  aLand of Israel.  aLivelihood.  aMaimonides.  aManumission.  aMasturbat